         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Buddha-god the teacher says to Tiṣya with a Brahmā-like voice:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having heard (that), the brahmin youths, astonished again, say:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... will be recognized (?) as very excellent. || Thereupon, the brahmin youth Ajita ... (in his) mind</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… will be recognized as very excellent. (121)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>630</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... How many years is (our teacher Bādhari) now old? || With a tender voice, the Buddha-god the teacher says:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... therefore he is now exactly (?) 120 years old. || Thereupon, the brahmin youth Dhonaki (only) in his mind</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... How many brahmin youths does he instruct in the Śāstras? || With a resounding voice, the Buddha-god the teacher says: Bādhari</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... From among them indeed you fifteen brahmin youths have come here. || Thereupon, the brahmin youth Mogharāja ... (in his) mind</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... is called the ‘top’. What is that? || With a bellowing voice, the Buddha-god the teacher says: || In the Ārśi-Niṣkramant [tune] ||</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in (studying the Law) ... and (even) a little joy in the good way of life of the jewel of the Community of monks, in whose thought ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... therefore you, oh brahmin youths, recognize that as the ‘top’ which is taught by the Buddha-god. 1 || Thereupon, Upaśima</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... asks by himself the question: What, oh venerable one, is ‘falling from the top’? || With a loud voice,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... If a being falls from the joy in the three jewels, he goes to vanishing and destruction.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">If a being falls from the joy in the three jewels, he goes to vanishing and destruction. (121)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>250</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... recognize (this), oh brahmin youths, as ‘falling from the top’! 1 || Thereupon, Paiṅgika and the other</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... deep and difficult problems connected with other heretical Śāstras, ... (in their) mind,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having pronounced, he says: || In the Niṣkramant [tune] || Those four truths</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... are to be understood (as being without) self. Having become the cause, the five aggregates</seg></seg></choice></p>
